'''腾格里信仰'''是[[突厥人|突厥人]]、[[蒙古族|蒙古人]]、[[匈人|匈人]]和[[匈奴|匈奴]]等[[中亚|中亚]][[游牧民族|游牧民族]]的传统信仰<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I-RTt0Q6AcYC&pg=PA151|publisher=Central European University Press|date=1999-03|isbn=978-963-9116-48-1|language=en|first=Andras|last=Rona-Tas|first2=Róna-Tas|last2=András|title=Hungarians and Europe in the Early Middle Ages: An Introduction to Early Hungarian History|pages=151|quote=There is no doubt that between the 6th and 9th centuries Tengrism was the religion among the nomads of the steppes|access-date=2020-08-24|archive-date=2020-09-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200922035131/https://books.google.com/books?id=I-RTt0Q6AcYC&pg=PA151|dead-url=no}}</ref>，带有[[萨满教|萨满教]]、[[泛靈論|泛灵信仰]]、[[圖騰|图腾崇拜]]和[[祖先崇拜|祖先崇拜]]色彩。腾格里信仰以[[一神论|一神论]]思想为主<ref>The spelling ''Tengrism'' is found in the 1960s, e.g. Bergounioux (ed.), ''Primitive and prehistoric religions'', Volume 140, Hawthorn Books, 1966, p. 80. ''Tengrianism'' is a reflection of the Russian term, {{lang|ru|Тенгрианство}}. It is reported in 1996 ("so-called Tengrianism") in Shnirelʹman (ed.), ''Who gets the past?: competition for ancestors among non-Russian intellectuals in Russia'', Woodrow Wilson Center Press, 1996, {{ISBN|978-0-8018-5221-3}}, [{{Google books |plainurl= yes |id=4iwHp8asmsdEC |page=31 }} p. 31] in the context of the nationalist rivalry over Bulgar legacy. The spellings ''Tengriism'' and ''Tengrianity'' are later, reported (deprecatingly, in scare quotes) in 2004 in ''Central Asiatic journal'', vol. 48–49 (2004), [{{Google books |plainurl=yes |id=GeRVAAAAYAAJ |page= 238}} p. 238].  The Turkish term {{lang|tr|Tengricilik}} is also found from the 1990s. Mongolian {{lang|mn|Тэнгэр шүтлэг}} is used in a 1999 biography of Genghis Khan (Boldbaatar et. al, {{lang|mn|Чингис хаан, 1162-1227}},  {{lang|mn|Хаадын сан}}, 1999, [{{Google books |plainurl= yes |id=OMIMAQAAMAAJ |page=18 }} p. 18]).</ref><ref>R. Meserve, Religions in the central Asian environment. In: [http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0012/001204/120455e.pdf History of Civilizations of Central Asia, Volume IV] {{Wayback|url=http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0012/001204/120455e.pdf |date=20160303221846 }}, The age of achievement: A.D. 750 to the end of the fifteenth century, Part Two: The achievements, p. 68:
*"''[...] The ‘imperial’ religion was more monotheistic, centred around the all-powerful god Tengri, the sky god.''"</ref>，崇拜中心神灵[[腾格里|腾格里]]。后由于受到[[佛教|佛教]]、[[印度教|印度教]]等影响，腾格里被加上各种称呼，分裂成为众多神灵，17世纪后甚至出现“九十九腾格里”的说法，有学者因而称之为“一神论和[[多神论|多神论]]的深刻结合”<ref name="PolyMono">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jAu9ttUqiJoC&pg=PA91|publisher=Stacey International|date=2003|isbn=978-1-900988-61-2|language=en|first=Michael|last=Fergus|first2=Janar|last2=Jandosova|title=Kazakhstan: Coming of Age|quote=[...] a profound combination of monotheism and polytheism that has come to be known as Tengrism.|page=91|access-date=2020-08-24|archive-date=2020-09-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200923115026/https://books.google.com/books?id=jAu9ttUqiJoC&pg=PA91|dead-url=no}}</ref>。在[[欧洲|欧洲]]，[[可萨人|可萨人]]、[[保加尔人|保加尔人]]、[[马扎尔人|马扎尔人]]<ref name= 'Fodor 2006'>Fodor István, [http://silver.drk.hu/MVT/letolt/vt6.pdf A magyarok ősi vallásáról (About the old religion of the Hungarians)] {{Wayback|url=http://silver.drk.hu/MVT/letolt/vt6.pdf |date=20160505081203 }} Vallástudományi Tanulmányok. 6/2004, Budapest, p. 17–19</ref>和[[阿瓦尔人|阿瓦尔人]]也曾信仰腾格里<ref>{{Cite book|chapter=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JmFetR5Wqd8C&pg=PA79|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|date=2010-12-15|isbn=978-1-4443-9254-8|language=en|first=John Anthony|last=McGuckin|title=The Encyclopedia of Eastern Orthodox Christianity|pages=79|access-date=2020-08-24|archive-date=2020-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200701183038/https://books.google.com/books?id=JmFetR5Wqd8C&pg=PA79|dead-url=no}}</ref>。腾格里信仰也是历史上[[突厥汗国|突厥汗国]]、[[西突厥|西突厥汗国]]、[[大保加利亚_(中世纪)|旧大保加利亚]]和[[保加利亚第一帝国|保加利亚第一帝国]]的主要宗教。

“腾格里”是古代中亚游牧民族对于天的称呼，与突厥同族的[[敕勒|敕勒]]发展出了“苍天”（Koke Tengri；蒙古语：Khukh Tengri）的概念<ref>《[[s:敕勒歌|敕勒歌]]》：“天苍苍，野茫茫”。</ref>，而蒙古人将蒙哥·腾格里（突厥语：Mangu Tangri；蒙古语：Mongke Tangri，汉语译作长生天）作为最高信仰。在[[中国|中国]]古代典籍中，“腾格里”一词最早出于[[匈奴|匈奴]]，写作“撑犁”<ref>《[[汉书|汉书]]·匈奴传》：“匈奴谓天为撑犁。”</ref><ref>《[[册府元龟|册府元龟]]·300》：“撑音田庾切。”</ref>。现代[[土耳其语|土耳其语]]也称腾格里信仰为“Göktanrı dini”，意为“天神教”，语源是蒙古语的“Khukh Tengri”，即“苍天”<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CORMAAAAMAAJ|publisher=Türk Dünyası Araştırmaları Vakfı|date=1992|isbn=978-975-498-051-6|language=tr|first=Mehmet|last=Eröz|title=Eski Türk dini (gök tanrı inancı) ve Alevîlik-Bektaşilik|access-date=2020-08-24|archive-date=2020-08-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200811071238/https://books.google.com/books?id=CORMAAAAMAAJ|dead-url=no}}</ref>。

腾格里信仰认为人的存在由“长生天”腾格里和大地母亲[[乌麦|乌麦]]维持，人需要诚实、有敬畏心地生活以调和自己的世界，并使自身的灵魂变得更为完美<ref name=":0" />。

腾格里信仰在其各信众部族中逐渐被[[伊斯兰教|伊斯兰教]]、[[藏传佛教|藏传佛教]]、[[摩尼教|摩尼教]]<ref>Buddhist studies review, Volumes 6-8, 1989, p. 164.</ref>和[[基督教|基督教]]等强势宗教取代，但自20世纪90年代起[[苏联解体|苏联解体]]起，中亚新建立的[[突厥语族|突厥语族]]共和国又开始重新推崇这种传统信仰<ref>{{cite book|last=Saunders|first=Robert A. and Vlad Strukov|title=Historical Dictionary of the Russian Federation|year=2010|publisher=Scarecrow Press|location=Lanham, MD|isbn=978-0-81085475-8|pages=412–13|url={{Google books |plainurl=yes |id= l_uAoNJiOMwC}}}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l_uAoNJiOMwC|publisher=Scarecrow Press|date=2010-05-13|isbn=978-0-8108-7460-2|language=en|first=Robert A.|last=Saunders|first2=Vlad|last2=Strukov|title=Historical Dictionary of the Russian Federation|pages=412-413|access-date=2020-08-24|archive-date=2020-09-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200913070548/https://books.google.com/books?id=l_uAoNJiOMwC|dead-url=no}}</ref>，在[[俄罗斯|俄罗斯]][[西伯利亚|西伯利亚]]的[[萨哈共和国|萨哈共和国]]、[[鞑靼斯坦共和国|鞑靼斯坦共和国]]、[[布里亚特共和国|布里亚特共和国]]和[[图瓦共和国|图瓦共和国]]等地也有复苏迹象，但不与既有信仰冲突<ref>Balkanlar'dan Uluğ Türkistan'a Türk halk inançları Cilt 1, Yaşar Kalafat, Berikan, 2007</ref>。[[吉尔吉斯共和国|吉尔吉斯共和国]]的前政府成员[[达斯坦·萨里古洛夫|达斯坦·萨里古洛夫]]成立了“腾格里军”（Tengir Ordo），旨在宣传腾格里信仰的传统价值；他还领导有一个声称有50万名信众的腾格里社群，支持国际腾格里信仰的研究<ref>{{cite web|title=High-Ranking Kyrgyz Official Proposes New National Ideology|url=http://www.jamestown.org/single/?no_cache=1&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=31177|accessdate=2013-02-19|last=McDermott|first=Roger|publisher=The Jamestown Foundation|archive-date=2012-09-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120912182739/http://www.jamestown.org/single/?no_cache=1&tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=31177|dead-url=no}}</ref>。

[[蒙古萨满信仰|蒙古萨满信仰]]（蒙古语：{{lang|mn|Бөө мөргөл}} ''Böö mörgöl''）以腾格里信仰为核心，也常常被直接称为“腾格里信仰”或“腾格里教”（Tengrism）<ref>Walther Heissig. The Religions of Mongolia. Routledge, 2000. ISBN 0710306857. P. 46</ref><ref>Michael Stausberg. Religion and Tourism: Crossroads, Destinations and Encounters. Routledge, 2010 (ISBN 0415549329), p.162: «Julie Steward, alias Sarangerel Odigon (1963-2006), a woman with a Mongolian (Buryat) mother and a German father, born in the United States, started to practice shamanism (or what she would refer to as "Tengerism") as an adult; she then moved to Mongolia where she strived to restore and reconstruct the "ancient and original" religion of the Mongolians. Among her major moves was the founding of a Mongolian Shamans' Association (Golomt Tuv) which gave Mongolian shamans a common platform and brought them into touch with shamans in other parts of the world, with the prospect of starting a shamanic world organization. Through some books Sarangerel also spread her Mongolian message to Western audiences. She traveled widely, giving lectures and holding workshops on Mongolian shamanism. Moreover, she started a Mongolian shamanic association of America (the Circle of Tengerism).»</ref>。

